text: "A 70-year-old man comes to the OPD due to increasing headaches, nausea, and vomiting. Medical history is significant for a transient ischemic attack that led to a right carotid endarterectomy 5 years ago. Blood pressure is 220/120 mm Hg and pulse is 70/min. Bilateral abdominal bruits are present. Blood testing in this patient would most likely show which of the following?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Low renin, low aldosterone, high angiotensin II, low potassium", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "High renin, high aldosterone, high angiotensin II, low potassium", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "C", "text": "Low renin, high aldosterone, high angiotensin II, low potassium", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "Low renin, low aldosterone, low angiotensin II, high potassium", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "Severe hypertension with bilateral abdominal bruits suggests bilateral renal artery stenosis, causing renovascular hypertension.<br><br>Renal hypoperfusion stimulates renin release, activating RAAS:<br><br>* \u2191 Renin\n* \u2191 Angiotensin II\n* \u2191 Aldosterone \u2192 Na\u207a retention & K\u207a loss (hypokalemia)<br><br>Thus, renovascular hypertension is characterized by high renin, high angiotensin II, high aldosterone, and low potassium.",
