text: "54-year-old woman comes to the emergency department due to several hours of severe epigastric abdominal pain radiating to her back. She has also had nausea and several episodes of vomiting. The patient has a history of occasional upper abdominal pain after eating but has never had such severe symptoms. She has no other medical issues and takes no medications. Temperature is 37.6 C (99.6 F), blood pressure is 110/66 mm Hg, pulse is 118/min, and respirations are 24/min. The patient appears to be in moderate distress. Mucous membranes are dry. The abdomen is distended with marked epigastric tenderness. Bowel sounds are decreased. Laboratory results are as follows:\nHematocrit: 48%\nLeukocytes: 18,800/mm\u00b3\nTotal bilirubin: 2.2 mg/dL\nAlkaline phosphatase: 370 U/L\nLipase: 2,192 U/L\nWhich of the following sets of renal findings are most expected in this patient?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Renin secretion high, Efferent arteriolar resistance high, Tubular sodium resporption high", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "B", "text": "Renin secretion high, Efferent arteriolar resistance low, Tubular sodium resporption high", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Renin secretion low, Efferent arteriolar resistance low, Tubular sodium resporption low", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "Renin secretion low, Efferent arteriolar resistance high, Tubular sodium resporption low", "is_correct": false}],
