text: "Which of the following changes are most likely to occur in this patient\u2019s kidney function after starting therapy with NSAID?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Decreased renal perfusion, decreased intraglomerular pressure, and constant filtration fraction", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "B", "text": "Increased  renal perfusion, decreased intraglomerular pressure, and decreased filtration fraction", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Decreased renal perfusion, increased intraglomerular pressure, and decreased filtration fraction", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "Decreased renal perfusion, decreased intraglomerular pressure, and constant filtration fraction", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "NSAIDs inhibit renal prostaglandin synthesis (PGE\u2082, PGI\u2082), which normally dilate the afferent arteriole.\nBlocking prostaglandins causes afferent arteriolar constriction, leading to:<br><br>* \u2193 Renal perfusion (RPF)\n* \u2193 Intraglomerular pressure\n* \u2193 GFR<br><br>Since both RPF and GFR fall proportionally, the filtration fraction remains relatively constant.\nThus, NSAIDs can precipitate AKI, especially in patients with CHF, CKD, or volume depletion.",
