text: "Goldblatt hypertension is best explained by which of the following mechanisms?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Increased sodium retention due to primary hyperaldosteronism", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Renal artery stenosis causing increased renin release and activation of the renin\u2013angiotensin\u2013aldosterone system", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "C", "text": "Decreased renal perfusion causing pressure natriuresis", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "Increased sympathetic discharge due to baroreceptor dysfunction", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "Goldblatt hypertension results from renal artery stenosis, which decreases renal perfusion pressure. This stimulates juxtaglomerular cells to release renin \u2192 activates the renin\u2013angiotensin\u2013aldosterone system (RAAS) \u2192 causes vasoconstriction, sodium and water retention \u2192 systemic hypertension.\nThus, Goldblatt hypertension is a classic model of secondary hypertension due to renovascular activation of RAAS.",
