text: "High Anion Gap Metabolic Acidosis (HAGMA) is not caused by:",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Diarrhea", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "B", "text": "Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA)", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Acute renal failure", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "Inborn errors of metabolism", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "<img src=\"https://corebtr-assets-production.s3.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/question_explanation/c632b999-aee6-418b-99f4-56800515fd07.png\" alt=\"Uploaded Image\">**If new acids enter the blood:**<br><br>* **H\u207a consumes HCO\u2083\u207b**\n* **Unmeasured anions rise**\n<br>\n    **\u2192 Anion gap increases**<br><br>High anion gap metabolic acidosis results from **accumulation of unmeasured acids** such as ketones, lactate, or retained uremic toxins.\n**DKA**, **acute renal failure**, and **inborn errors of metabolism** all cause HAGMA.\n**Diarrhea** causes **normal anion gap (hyperchloremic) metabolic acidosis** due to bicarbonate loss.<br><br>| **Feature** | **HAGMA** | **NAGMA** |\n| ------- | ----- | ----- |\n| Cause | Acid accumulation | HCO\u2083\u207b loss |\n| Cl\u207b | Normal | \u2191 |\n| Examples | DKA, AKI, toxins | Diarrhea, RTA |",
